    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv. For each file, provide a compact summary containing: total row count, minimum and maximum timestamp, up to 10 distinct cmdb_id values, up to 10 distinct KPI/trace/log names (use kpi_name for metric.csv, trace_name for trace.csv, log_name for log.csv), and up to 5 sample rows. For error_logs.csv, include up to 5 distinct cmdb_id and up to 5 sample messages. Keep outputs concise and tabular (CSV or dict-like). Do not convert timestamps to datetimes."
}

{
    "analysis": "The provided file summaries show metric.csv (144,252 rows), trace.csv (36,760 rows), log.csv (1,812 rows) and error_logs.csv (2,016 rows). All files' timestamp ranges (min 1647748800 to max ~1647750599) cover the suspected incident window (March 20, 2022 12:00–12:30 local). Next we must follow the prescribed workflow: compute global thresholds on the full series first, then extract data for the incident window. To narrow candidates, we should compute global P95 thresholds per component-KPI (component = cmdb_id, KPI name as in each file) across the full available series in each telemetry file, and then inspect the top candidates by threshold severity. The next executor step will compute these P95 values for metric, trace, and log files and return compact top-N aggregates for further anomaly detection.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For each of metric.csv, trace.csv, and log.csv calculate global P95 (95th percentile) for every unique component-KPI time series without filtering by time. Specifically: \n1) metric.csv: group by (cmdb_id,kpi_name) and compute p95, count, min_timestamp, max_timestamp; return top 20 rows sorted by p95 descending with columns [cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95, count, min_timestamp, max_timestamp].\n2) trace.csv: group by (cmdb_id,trace_name) and compute p95, count, min_timestamp, max_timestamp; return top 20 rows sorted by p95 descending with columns [cmdb_id, trace_name, p95, count, min_timestamp, max_timestamp].\n3) log.csv: group by (cmdb_id,log_name) and compute p95, count, min_timestamp, max_timestamp; return top 20 rows sorted by p95 descending with columns [cmdb_id, log_name, p95, count, min_timestamp, max_timestamp].\nAlso report the number of distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name)/(cmdb_id,trace_name)/(cmdb_id,log_name) groups found in each file. Keep outputs compact and limit each returned table to at most 20 rows."
}

{
    "analysis": "We computed global P95 per (cmdb_id,KPI) for metric, trace and log files across the full available series. Top global-P95 groups include many runtime/java and system.disk KPIs in metric.csv, very large row_count KPIs for frontend in trace.csv and log.row_count for frontends in log.csv. According to the workflow, the next step is to extract data within the incident window (March 20, 2022 12:00–12:30 UTC+8) and detect anomalies by comparing each group's incident-window values against its global thresholds. We should check both high-side breaches (>= P95) and low-side drops (<= P05) because traffic/business KPIs may show failures as sudden drops. The goal of the next query is to produce a compact list of candidate faulty component-KPI groups with earliest anomaly time, severity, and basic counts so we can narrow candidates for deeper trace/log inspection.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, trace.csv, and log.csv and the previously computed global thresholds, do the following: \n1) For each unique (cmdb_id, KPI_name) group in each file, compute global P95 and global P05 using the full series (if not already present). \n2) Filter rows to the incident window from \"2022-03-20 12:00:00+08:00\" to \"2022-03-20 12:30:00+08:00\" (inclusive). \n3) For each group, detect anomalies in the window where value >= P95 (mark as 'high') or value <= P05 (mark as 'low'). For each group with at least one anomaly, return one row with columns: [file, cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_type, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, anomaly_count_in_window, extreme_value_in_window (max for 'high', min for 'low'), global_p95, global_p05, severity_ratio], where severity_ratio = abs(extreme_value - threshold)/threshold (threshold = p95 for 'high', p05 for 'low'). \n4) Return up to top 20 rows across all files sorted by severity_ratio descending. Also include at the top the total number of groups that had anomalies in the window for each file (metric_count, trace_count, log_count). Keep output compact."
}

{
    "analysis": "We computed global thresholds (P95/P05) and detected many anomalies inside the incident window. The highest-severity anomalies are trace duration spikes (severity_ratio up to ~78) involving frontend-1 -> cartservice-0 (trace.to_cartservice-0.duration_mean) and cartservice-0 (trace.from_frontend-1.duration_mean). Several cartservice.* and frontend-1 trace duration metrics show large short bursts at earliest timestamps around 1647748920–1647749580. In parallel, metric anomalies show elevated container memory/fs writes and network receive on components scheduled on node-5 (currencyservice-2, emailservice*, paymentservice*, shippingservice*, redis-cart2-0), suggesting potential node-level I/O or network issues impacting some containers. According to the workflow, we should localize root cause at service/container level next using traces to identify the most downstream faulty component. The immediate next step is to inspect detailed trace records around the candidate trace groups (frontend-1 -> cartservice, and cartservice self/from_frontend traces) within the incident window to verify fault duration, earliest occurrence, and which component shows the first sustained anomaly.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From trace.csv, filter rows within the incident window \"2022-03-20 12:00:00+08:00\" to \"2022-03-20 12:30:00+08:00\". Restrict to trace_name matching any of these exact names or patterns: trace.to_cartservice-0.duration_mean, trace.to_cartservice-1.duration_mean, trace.to_cartservice-2.duration_mean, trace.from_frontend-1.duration_mean, trace.self.duration_mean for cmdb_id in cartservice-0, cartservice-1, cartservice-2, and also include frontend-1 trace.self.duration_mean and trace.to_cartservice-*.duration_mean for frontend-1. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) group return: count_in_window, earliest_timestamp, latest_timestamp, max_value_in_window, mean_value_in_window. Also include up to 10 sample rows (timestamp, cmdb_id, trace_name, value) chosen from the window (but keep total samples <=10). Return groups sorted by max_value_in_window desc and limit to top 20 groups. Keep output compact."
}

{
    "analysis": "We inspected trace groups in the incident window and found the largest duration spikes involve frontend-1 calling cartservice (to_cartservice-*.duration_mean and cartservice from_frontend-1.duration_mean). These trace spikes are short, high-severity bursts (max values up to ~0.003–0.0049) with earliest anomalies around timestamp 1647748920. Separately, metric-level anomaly detection earlier revealed many container-level anomalies whose KPI names include \"container.node-5.*\" (memory, fs_writes, network_receive, etc.) across multiple services (currencyservice-2, emailservice*, paymentservice-0, shippingservice-0, redis-cart2-0). That suggests a node-level resource anomaly on node-5 that affected multiple pods. According to the diagnosis rules, we should (1) verify which pods are running on node-5 and had metric anomalies in the window, (2) check whether the cartservice pods implicated by traces are on node-5, and (3) correlate earliest anomaly timestamps between node-5 metric anomalies and the trace duration spikes to determine causality and the root cause occurrence time. The next atomic step is to enumerate the pods (cmdb_id) that show container.* KPIs tied to node-5 and had anomalies in the incident window, with earliest anomaly time and severity, so we can see whether cartservice pods are among those affected and if node-5 anomalies precede the trace spikes.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv: filter to rows within the incident window \"2022-03-20 12:00:00+08:00\" to \"2022-03-20 12:30:00+08:00\" and to kpi_name values that contain the substring \"container.node-5\". For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) group compute: anomaly_count_in_window (count of rows where value >= that group's global P95 computed from the full series), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (min timestamp where value >= P95), max_value_in_window, global_p95 (from full series), and severity_ratio = (max_value_in_window - global_p95)/global_p95. Return: total number of distinct cmdb_id affected; and up to top 20 rows sorted by severity_ratio desc with columns [cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, global_p95, severity_ratio]. Keep output compact."
}

{
    "analysis": "We found widespread container-level anomalies tied to metrics whose KPI names contain \"container.node-5\" affecting 35 distinct cmdb_id (pods) during the incident window; top severity groups include currencyservice-2 (memory_mapped_file, fs_writes) with earliest anomalies around 1647749000 and some groups at 1647750000. Trace analysis revealed high-severity, short-duration spikes in frontend-1 -> cartservice traces (to_cartservice-*.duration_mean and cartservice from_frontend-1.duration_mean) with earliest anomalous timestamps reported earlier around 1647748920. This suggests two hypotheses: (A) a node-5 resource issue impacted many pods and caused downstream latency, or (B) trace-level latency spikes in frontend/cartservice occurred first and node-5 anomalies are secondary or unrelated. To determine causality we must compare earliest anomaly occurrence times precisely using the same global-P95-based anomaly definition for each group (global thresholds computed from full series). The next step should produce the earliest P95-breach timestamp for (1) all \"container.node-5\" metric groups and (2) the implicated trace groups (frontend-1 and cartservice-0/1/2 trace names), so we can tell which level deviated first.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Compute earliest P95-breach timestamps (using each group's global P95 computed from the full series) within the incident window \"2022-03-20 12:00:00+08:00\" to \"2022-03-20 12:30:00+08:00\" as follows:\n1) Metric set: for every (cmdb_id, kpi_name) where kpi_name contains \"container.node-5\", find the earliest timestamp in the window where value >= that group's global P95. Return rows [cmdb_id, kpi_name, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, anomaly_count_in_window, max_value_in_window, global_p95], but only for groups that have at least one breach. Also return the minimum earliest_anomaly_timestamp across all these groups (label it node5_earliest).\n2) Trace set: for these exact trace groups: frontend-1 (trace.self.duration_mean, trace.to_cartservice-0.duration_mean, trace.to_cartservice-1.duration_mean, trace.to_cartservice-2.duration_mean) and cartservice-0/1/2 (trace.from_frontend-1.duration_mean, trace.self.duration_mean), for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) find the earliest timestamp in the window where value >= that group's global P95. Return rows [cmdb_id, trace_name, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, anomaly_count_in_window, max_value_in_window, global_p95] for groups with breaches, and also return the minimum earliest_anomaly_timestamp across these trace groups (label it trace_earliest).\nLimit output to top 50 rows total and keep results compact. Also return node5_earliest and trace_earliest as epoch seconds."
}

{
    "analysis": "We compared global-P95 breaches for container.node-5 metrics and the implicated trace groups. The Executor found widespread container-level P95 breaches tied to \"container.node-5.*\" affecting 35+ pods and many (2,108) container.node-5 KPI groups within the incident window, with an earliest breach equal to the window start (1647748800). Trace groups for frontend-1 and cartservice-0/1/2 also show P95 breaches inside the window and their earliest breach timestamp also equals the window start (1647748800). This means both node-5 related container anomalies and trace latency spikes appear concurrently at the start of the investigated window. To localize root cause we must use logs to determine which anomalies show error logs or messages and which component first shows operational errors — especially checking cartservice and frontend pods (which show trace spikes) and a representative set of pods with node-5 container anomalies (e.g., currencyservice-2, paymentservice-0, emailservice-1). If logs show errors originating from node-level resource exhaustion (e.g., OOMs, disk errors, I/O timeouts) on node-5 or show container process terminations or read/write errors, that will support node-5 as the root cause. Conversely, if only cartservice/frontend show errors while node-5 containers merely have elevated metrics without error logs, the root cause may be in the application layer. Therefore we need targeted log inspection next.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Within the incident window \"2022-03-20 12:00:00+08:00\" to \"2022-03-20 12:30:00+08:00\":\n1) From error_logs.csv: filter rows where cmdb_id is one of [\"frontend-1\",\"cartservice-0\",\"cartservice-1\",\"cartservice-2\",\"currencyservice-2\",\"paymentservice-0\",\"emailservice-1\"]. For each cmdb_id return: total_message_count, earliest_message_timestamp, up to 5 distinct sample messages (trim long messages), and the top 3 message prefixes (first ~80 chars) with their counts. Limit output to these cmdb_ids only.\n2) From log.csv: filter rows in the same window for the same cmdb_id list and for log_name equal to \"log.error_count\" (and also include \"log.row_count\" for context). For each (cmdb_id, log_name) return: sum(value) over the window, earliest_timestamp where value>0, max_value, and count_of_nonzero_entries. Return only rows where sum(value)>0 (i.e., actual errors), limit to top 20 rows.\nReturn compact aggregate tables for error_logs and log aggregates. Do not return full raw series."
}

{
    "analysis": "We followed the prescribed workflow: computed global thresholds (P95/P05) for metrics/traces/logs, filtered the incident window (2022-03-20 12:00–12:30 +08), and detected anomalies. Key findings so far: (1) trace-level high-severity latency spikes (highest severity_ratio ~77) involve frontend-1 calling cartservice (frontend-1 trace.self.duration_mean and trace.to_cartservice-*.duration_mean, plus cartservice from_frontend-* traces). (2) Many container metrics with KPI names containing \"container.node-5\" show widespread P95 breaches across ~35 pods and thousands of container-node-5 KPI groups in the window, indicating a node-5 resource anomaly affecting many pods. (3) Log analysis shows frontend-1 is the only component among targeted candidates with大量 error logs in the window (log.error_count sum=545) and error_messages like \"failed to retrieve...\"; cartservice pods had no error_logs entries. (4) Earliest P95 breaches for both node-5 metrics and the implicated traces are at/near the window start (epoch 1647748800), so timing alone does not clearly separate cause and effect. Using the diagnosis rules: when faults exist at different levels, choose the level with the most significant deviation — traces for frontend-1 show the largest deviation (>>50%) and frontend-1 is the only component with substantial error logs, while cartservice has trace latency but no error logs. This makes frontend-1 the leading candidate for the root cause component, but we have not yet confirmed the underlying resource reason (CPU/memory/network/process termination, etc.). Before finalizing, we must verify frontend-1’s resource KPIs (container CPU/memory/network/IO/process) in the incident window to identify the specific reason. Therefore the investigation is not yet complete.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Within the incident window \"2022-03-20 12:00:00+08:00\" to \"2022-03-20 12:30:00+08:00\":\n1) From metric.csv, filter to cmdb_id == \"frontend-1\" and to kpi_name that start with \"container.\" (i.e., all container-level KPIs for the frontend-1 pod). For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) group compute: global_p95 (from full series), earliest_timestamp_in_window where value >= global_p95, anomaly_count_in_window (count of breaches), max_value_in_window, and severity_ratio = (max_value_in_window - global_p95)/global_p95. Return only groups with at least one breach in the window. Limit output to top 20 rows sorted by severity_ratio desc, and include the overall earliest breach timestamp for frontend-1 (the minimum earliest_timestamp_in_window). Keep output compact."
}

{
    "analysis": "We followed the required workflow: computed global thresholds on full series, filtered the incident window (2022-03-20 12:00–12:30 +08), performed metric anomaly detection, trace analysis and log inspection. Key observations: (1) The largest deviations (highest severity ratios) are trace-level latency spikes involving frontend-1 (trace.self.duration_mean) and frontend-1 -> cartservice calls (trace.to_cartservice-*.duration_mean) with severity ratios up to ~78x the P95. (2) Frontend-1 is the only inspected component with abundant error log entries in the window (log.error_count sum = 545; earliest error log at 1647749000). (3) Many container metrics with KPI names containing \"container.node-5\" show P95 breaches across many pods (35+ pods; thousands of container-KPI groups), indicating a node-5 resource anomaly impacting multiple containers. (4) frontend-1’s container-level metrics show network and CPU anomalies (notably container_network_receive_MB with severity_ratio > 1) and frontend-1 is scheduled on node-5 (its container KPIs include \"container.node-5\"). Timing: earliest P95 breaches for both trace anomalies and node-5 metrics appear at or near the window start (epoch 1647748800). Applying the localization rules: when faults exist at different levels, select the level with the most significant deviation (trace-level deviations >>50%); among container-level candidates, use traces and logs to select the most downstream faulty container. Traces + logs consistently point to frontend-1 as the most downstream faulty container with the biggest deviation and the only significant error log signal. Node-5 anomalies are broad and likely contributory (network/resource stress), but the trace+log evidence localizes the root cause to the frontend-1 pod. The most plausible underlying reason supported by metrics is network resource stress on node-5 (container network receive/transmit spikes), causing increased request latency/timeouts at frontend-1 and resulting error logs and elevated trace durations.",
    "completed": "True",
    "instruction": "Root cause summary: root cause component = frontend-1 (pod). Root cause occurrence time = epoch 1647748800 (2022-03-20 12:00:00 +08). Root cause reason = container network latency / network resource saturation affecting frontend-1 (frontend-1 shows large trace-level latency spikes and error logs; many container.node-5 network KPIs also breached P95 across pods, indicating node-5 network stress that led to frontend-1 request timeouts and high latencies)."
}

